[0.110, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[2.005, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "an Array (shape [2], 2 items)\r\n 1 : 'use auto named arg ; options \"NOCOMMANDS\" ; say \"Hello\"'\r\n 2 : 'if var(\"result\") then return result'\r\n"]
[2.004, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34m/*\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mBy convention, the higher-order functions are passing the named parameters\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.002, "o", "\u001b[1;34m\"item\" and \"index\". Their values are also passed as positional arguments.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe callee has the choice: using the auto named arguments, or using the positional\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34marguments. The callee has a total control over which arguments he accepts.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mIf its constraints on positional and/or named arguments are incompatible with\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mthe expectations of the higher-order function then an error will be raised.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m*/\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "ooRexx[bash]> "]
